    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA364-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu talaimakaḷ piriviṭai melintatu. [G1+2: tōḻi tūtu viṭuvatu payaṉ].</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how SHE became weak in the time of separation. [G1+2: The gist is the confidante’s sending out a messenger.]</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA364">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            colliya paruvaṅ kaḻintaṉ ṟellaiyu</l>
<l>            mayaṅkiru ṇaṭunāṇ maṅkulō ṭoṉṟi</l>
<l>            yārkali vāṉa nīrpotin tiyaṅkap</l>
<l>            paṉiyiṉ vāṭaiyoṭu muṉivuvan tiṟuppa</l>
<l>            viṉṉa ciṉṉāṭ kaḻiyiṟ paṉṉāḷ</l>
<l>            vāḻaleṉ vāḻi tōḻi yūḻi</l>
<l>            ṉurumicai yaṟiyāc ciṟucen nāvi</l>
<l>            ṉīrmaṇi yiṉkura lūrnaṉi yiyampap</l>
<l>            pallā tanta kallāk kōvalar</l>
<l>            koṉṟaiyan tīṅkuḻaṉ maṉṟutō ṟiyampa</l>
<l>            vuyircelat tuṉaitaru mālai</l>
<l>            ceyirtīr māriyō ṭoruṅkutalai variṉē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>            The season [he] had spoken of has passed by.</l>
<l>            If a few [more] pleasing days pass by,</l>
<l>            while the water is bundled [and] stirs in the fully bustling sky,</l>
<l>            one with the clouds at midday of confusing darkness even by daylight,</l>
<l>            while affliction comes with the chilly<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">paṉiyiṉ vāṭaiyoṭu</term>: what to make here of the oblique mark in <term xml:lang="ta">paṉiyiṉ</term>? Were it not for the fact that the north wind is decidedly perceived as something unpleasant, I would feel induced to split <term xml:lang="ta">paṉi</term> <term xml:lang="ta">iṉ</term>, "chilly sweet north wind".</note> north wind [and] tarries,</l>
<l>        I won’t live for many days, oh friend,</l>
<l>            – when together with the blemishless(?) showers</l>
<l>        evening comes up in a haste, for [my] life to go,</l>
<l>            while from every cow-shed the sweet Laburnum flute is sounding,</l>
<l>            of the untaught cowherds who have brought [back] many cows,</l>
<l>            while in the village the sweet voices of [their] wet bells with small red</l>
<l>             tongues,</l>
<l>            that don’t know of the sound of thunder, sound abundantly in turn.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
